The paper deals with the problem of inverse reinforcement learning, which is a subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The use of subgoals and the modeling of behavior in a spatio-temporal context suggest that the paper may also be relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and robotics (cs.RO). The probabilistic nature of the model and its potential application in active learning suggest that it may also be relevant to systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the use of demonstrations and trajectory data suggests that the paper may also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV).
